<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Samplings from 25 restaurants will be available at Menlo Park's
Connoisseur's Marketplace next weekend.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  FAMILY; CHILDREN; ENTERTAINMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE mid-Peninsula will be alive again today as the second day of the Los Altos
Arts and Wine Festival gets under way. And next weekend Menlo Park will launch
its Connoisseur's Marketplace on Saturday and Sunday. Both events are being
held on the main streets of their respective towns and both have special
events for children, creating a hometown arena for family outings.;    (check)
Jazz is the featured entertainment today at the Los Altos Arts and Wine
Festival, with the San Jose Jazz Society playing from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. and
the Jazz Workshop from 1 to 3 p.m. on the main stage, between Main and State
streets off of Third Street, Los Altos. A special children's stage provides
continuous entertainment with the Magic Pearl Puppets, Jay the Juggler, and
Bethie, who performs children's songs. A limited supply of free kazoos will be
distributed at 1 p.m. today followed by a sing-along. The children's stage is
at the intersection of Main and State streets, off San Antonio Road, Los
Altos. There will be 360 arts and crafts booths lining Main Street along with
booths featuring Santa Cruz Mountain wines, international cuisine and a
variety of beers. Admission and parking are free.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WINE AND SONG IN THE AIR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Family Clipboard
Things to do  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (check) Next weekend two stages of musical entertainment are being planned
for the Connoisseur's Marketplace in Menlo Park. Culinary samplings from 25
restaurants and California wines will be featured. Entertainment starts at 10
a.m. each day at the El Camino Stage, corner of El Camino Real and Santa Cruz
Avenue, and the Fremont Park Stage, corner of University and Santa Cruz
avenues. Two hundred craftspeople will show their creations, and there will be
a barnyard petting zoo, clowns, face painting and art demonstrations. Free
admission and parking.;    (check) If the family feels like a drive to the
country, try the Summer Fine Arts and Quality Craft Festival from 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. today in San Juan Bautista. Works by 250 artisans will be displayed.
Ventriloquist Skip Hines and his puppet, Dusty, will entertain the kids with
free balloons and face painting while adults enjoy the bands Way Out West and
High Strung. Foods include barbecued spareribs, sausage sandwiches, shish
kebabs and beer and homemade ice cream and fresh-squeezed lemonade. Free
admission.;    (check) Other family activities this week include:;    Events;
Families Arts Day.  This free event Saturday is designed for all ages. There
will be 10 hands-on arts booths for children, live entertainment (10:30
a.m.-2:30 p.m.) and activities that include musical spoons, silk screening and
origami. Refreshments will be available. Sponsored by the Arts Council of San
Mateo County and the Redwood City Parks, Recreation and Community Service
department. Gates open at 10 a.m. at Red Morton park, behind the Community
Activities Building, 1400 Roosevelt Ave., Redwood City.;    Obon Festival. 
This traditional Japanese Festival of Lanterns is in its second day today at
the San Jose Buddhist Church, 640 N. Fifth St., San Jose. Food booths open at
1 p.m., followed by games for both adults and children, a temple program, the
Minyo singing group, San Jose Taiko Drum group, Chidori Band concert and obon
dancing. The foods include sushi, tempura, teriyaki, barbecued chicken,
skewered teriyaki beef, noodles and strawberry short cake. Because of parking
limitations, festivalgoers are encouraged to use light rail and get off at the
Ayer-Japantown station. Free admission.;    Entertainment; "Joseph and the
Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat."  This play is presented by the Palo Alto
Children's Theater at 7:30 p.m. Thursday and Friday and at 2:30 and 7:30 p.m.
Saturday at the main Theater, Foothill College, 12345 El Monte Road, Los Altos
Hills. Admission is $3 adults, $2 children. Call (415) 948-4444.;    Mexican
Museum.  Performances and art activities for both children and parents. Noon-5
p.m. today, Fort Mason Center, Building D, Laguna Street and Marina Boulevard,
San Francisco. Free. (415) 441-0445.;    "Peter Pan."  Presented by Los Altos
Youth Theater. 8 p.m. Friday and 2 and 8 p.m. Saturday, Spangenberg
Auditorium, Gunn High School, 780 Arastradero Road, Palo Alto. Admission is $6
adults; $4 children 4-12 and seniors. Reserved seats only. (415) 948-6903.;   
"The Princess and the Magic Pea."  A musical adaptation of a popular fairy
tale. Performers are ages 9-16. Curtain times 7:30 p.m. Fridays and Saturdays,
4 p.m. Sundays. Alameda Children's Musical Theatre, 1912 Central Ave.,
Alameda. Play runs through July 28. Admission is $7; $5 for seniors, teens,
military personnel and disabled people; $4 for children under 12. For
reservations call (415) 521-6965.;    Exhibits;  Children's Discovery Museum 
announces new summer hours of 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Wednesday through Saturdays;
to 8 p.m. Thursdays and from noon to 5 p.m. Sundays through Aug. 27. Tuesdays
the museum is open to pre-booked youth groups only. The museum features
hands-on interactive exhibits and programs. Located at Woz Way and Auzerais
Street, San Jose. Admission is $6 adults, $3 children ages 4-18; 3 and under
are free. (408) 298-5437.;    Inside Active Volcanoes  is the timely exhibit
at Lawrence Hall of Science, University of California, Berkeley, with
demonstrations of Hall-made volcano eruptions, art activities planned for 1-3
p.m. Wednesday. Spectacular photographs and video footage of the Mount St.
Helens and Kilauea volcanoes will be shown. Admission is $4 adults, $3 seniors
and youths ages 7-18, $2 ages 3-6. (415) 642-5133.;    Upcoming; "Childhood
Memories"  is the theme for the 47th annual Santa Clara County Fair, July 25
through Aug. 11. A special promotion on Butler Amusements' Carnival Coupon
Books is available this year. If purchased before July 24, the book containing
33 ride coupons is on sale for half-price at $10. Season passes, $19.95, also
entitle holders to general fair admission as often as they like through the
run of the fair. Call (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277. Regular admission at
the county fair will be $6.50 general (ages 17-59), $4 for seniors (60 and
over) and juniors (6-16).;    An All You Can Eat Ice Cream Social  will be
held 1:30 to 4:30 p.m. July 28 at the Community School of Music and Arts, 253
Martens Ave., Mountain View. A family fun afternoon of sweet surprises by
Dreyer's, Double Rainbow, Baskin-Robbins, yogurt from J. Higby's, toppings
from Smucker's, a children's art exhibit, hands-on activities, a sound sampler
for kids to try out musical instruments are all planned. Advance tickets are
$4 adults, $2.50 children; at the gate, $5 adults, $3 children, with family
attendance not to exceed $15. (415) 961-0342.  </TEXT>
